dataIdInfo.idAbs: Draw class signatures as ellipses in a series of two dimensional graphs and outputs to a PDF file.

tool.name: DrawSignatures

param.name: in_signature_file
param.dialogReference:
Input signature file whose class signatures are used to produce ellipses.

A .gsg extension is required.
param.pythonReference:
Input signature file whose class signatures are used to produce ellipses.

A .gsg extension is required.

param.name: out_ellipses
param.dialogReference:
The output ellipses PDF file.

The extension should be .pdf.
param.pythonReference:
The output ellipses PDF file.

The extension should be .pdf.

param.name: n_std
param.dialogReference:
Number of standard deviations that are used to determine the sizes of the major and minor axes of the ellipses.

The value can be integer or floating point. The larger the value is, the larger the output ellipses will be. Although there are no upper value restrictions for it, it is not usually effective to enter values greater than 3. The default value is 1.
param.pythonReference:
Number of standard deviations that are used to determine the sizes of the major and minor axes of the ellipses.

The value can be integer or floating point. The larger the value is, the larger the output ellipses will be. Although there are no upper value restrictions for it, it is not usually effective to enter values greater than 3. The default value is 1.

param.name: show_classid
param.dialogReference:
Specifies whether class ids should be shown at the center of the ellipses.

  • Checked — the class ids will be shown.

  • Unchecked — the class ids will not be shown.
param.pythonReference:
Specifies whether class ids should be shown at the center of the ellipses.

  • CLASSID — the class ids will be shown.

  • NO_CLASSID — the class ids will not be shown.

tool.summary: Draw class signatures as ellipses in a series of two dimensional graphs and outputs to a PDF file.
tool.usage:
• This tool displays the class signatures for every layer combination in the form of ellipses. The ellipses outline the boundary of the sample distribution defined by a specified number of standard deviations.

  • The ellipses are displayed in two-dimensional space, with the axes representing the layers of a signature file. Each ellipse depicts a class signature.

  • The location and shape of each ellipse in a two dimensional-graph space are defined by the mean and standard deviation of a class signature in each layer combination.

  • The minimum valid number of class signatures in the input signature file is 2. There is no limit to the maximum number of classes.

  • The number entered for the n_std can be an integer as well as the floating-point value. When a low value is input for n_std (such as 1), smaller ellipses are drawn with less overlap because all cells used to produce the plot will be close to the class mean. Although there are no upper value restrictions for n_std, it is not usually effective to enter values greater than 3.

  • The range of values on both axes is automatically adjusted relative to the ranges set by the extents of ellipses in the layers corresponding to each axis. Since the graphs are based on the extent of the ellipses, the graph showing the distribution of signatures is conveniently stretched. The minimums and maximums of the ellipse extents determine the minimums and maximums on the respective x- and y-axis of the graph.

  • The input signature file can be obtained from the Create Signatures tool, the Iso Cluster tool, or the Image Classification toolbar.

  • The following environment settings affect this tool: Current Workspace, Scratch Workspace.

scriptExample.title: Draw Signatures example (Python window)
scriptExample.para: This example creates an ellipses file from an input signature file and outputs it to a PDF file.
scriptExample.code:
#Add toolbox to arcpy arcpy.AddToolbox(r"C:\pythontoolbox\Spatial Analyst Supplemental Tools.pyt")
#Execute DrawSignature tool arcpy.DrawSignatures_sas(r'C:\ToolData\redlands.gsg', r'c:\temp\test1.pdf', 1, 'CLASSID')

scriptExample.title: Draw Signatures example (Stand-alone script)
scriptExample.para: This example creates an ellipses file from an input signature file and outputs it to a PDF file.
scriptExample.code:
#Add toolbox to arcpy arcpy.AddToolbox(r"C:\pythontoolbox\Spatial Analyst Supplemental Tools.pyt")
inSigFile = r'C:\ToolData\redlands.gsg' outEllipses = r'c:\temp\test2.pdf' nStd = 1 showID = "NO_CLASSID"
#Execute DrawSignature tool arcpy.DrawSignatures_sas(inSigFile, outEllipses, nStd, showID)
